1,3-Oxazolidin-2-ones (OAOs) are important as structural elements in modern antibiotics, the first of which was linezolid targeting bacterial protein synthesis (

). Likewise, several OAOs are important as auxiliaries in chiral synthesis (

). They are also known as Evans auxiliaries and used for controlling aldol reactions (

). In this report, we argue that this class of compounds is also formed from enzymatic turnover of glucosinolates, a group of natural 
S
-glucosides (

; 

).

It is well known that a related group of heterocycles, the substituted 1,3-oxazolidine-2-thiones (OATs), are found in many glucosinolate-containing plants. Both OAOs and OATs are named as deriving from the parent heterocycle azolidine (
Fig. 1
), explaining the middle ‘A’ in our abbreviations. Penicillin contains a third pattern, a thiazolidine ring (
Fig. 1
). Natural diversity of heterocyclic secondary metabolites was studied by several researchers, inspired by the remarkable progress in penicillin chemistry in the first half of the 20th century. Two reports independently showed that OATs were formed via cyclisation of 
b
-hydroxyalkyl isothiocyanates produced from 
b
-hydroxyalkyl glucosinolates (

; 

). For example, (
R
)-5-phenylOAT (( 
R
)-barbarin, 
2
) is formed via a never isolated 
b
-hydroxy isothiocyanate derived from (
S
)-2-hydroxy-2-phenylethylglucosinolate (glucobarbarin, 
1
) (
Fig. 2
) (

; Agerbirk and Olsen, 2015). The enantiomer, (
S
)-barbarin, is formed from the epimeric glucosinolate epiglucobarbarin (

). Benzyl-activating substitution of glucobarbarins change the 
type
of hydrolysis product to a 1,3-thiazolidin-2-one (TAO), an additional heterocycle in this plant group (
Fig. 1
) (Agerbirk and Olsen, 2015). Recently, 5- phenylTAO was also detected at low levels after fractionation of 

B. vulgaris

extracts, but not in initial analysis of the extract (

), perhaps indicating very low levels or formation as an artifact. Indeed, a thermally induced rearrangement of 5- phenylOAT to 5-phenylTAO is also well established (

; 

).

Glucosinolates are found throughout the order 

Brassicales (
Blazevic et al., 2015
)

, with around 144 documented structures reported by 2016 (

; 

; 

; Agerbirk et al., 2015; 

; 

; 

) and a further reported 3‾5 structures from 2017, including (the isothiocyanate corresponding to) 5- phenylpentylglucosinolate (

) and 4-hydroxy-3,5- dimethoxybenzylglucosinolate (

). Although some structural features seem to be restricted to smaller taxonomic groups, there is also a great redundancy in structures found in widely separated taxonomic groups (

; 

). A widespread structural feature is 
b
-hydroxylation of the glucosinolate side-chain catalyzed by GS-OH enzymes (

; 

; 

; 

). Indeed, the 
b
-hydroxylated glucosinolate glucobarbarin (
1
) is found in 
Resedaceae
(e.g. 

Reseda luteola

L.) (

; 

) as well as in 
Brassicaceae
(e.g. most or all 

Barbarea
spp.

and some accessions of watercress, 

Nasturtium
of 
fi
- cinale

R.Br) (

; 

; 

).

From 

R. luteola

, two alkaloids were described in an early report (

). One was a substituted OAT, while the other was a substituted OAO, a further heterocyclic ring in the order 
Brassicales
(
Fig. 1
). The OAT was named resedinine, but was identical to barbarin. Hence the older name has priority, and the name resedinine should be abandoned. The OAO was named resedine (
3
) and identified as 5-phenylOAO (
Fig. 2
). Relations to plant biochemistry or glucosinolate turnover were not investigated.

Of the many known OATs in the 
Brassicales
, one has received particular attention: (
S
)-5-vinylOAT (( 
S
)-goitrin) formed from the glucosinolate progoitrin (( 
R
)-2-hydroxybut-3-enylglucosinolate) in oilseed rape (

). Despite decades of breeding efforts to lower levels of progoitrin and goitrin (

), these metabolites remain a limiting factor for the use of protein from oilseed rape in fodder. Some of the antinutritional effects of goitrin and other OATs seem to be related to disturbance of iodine metabolism and catalysis of nitrite reactions in mammals (reviewed in 

; 

). A recent investigation has broadened the range of known effects of OATs (

).

Glucosinolate hydrolysis is catalyzed by isoenzymes of thioglucoside glucohydrolase (E.C. 3.2.1.147) commonly known as myrosinases. Myrosinase-catalyzed complete turnover of glucosinolates happens after tissue disruption, and is caused by the mixing of enzyme and substrate that were spatially separated in intact plants (Wittstock et al., 2016a; b). Classical myrosinases of the “TGG” group were for many years regarded as the sole enzymes catalyzing this reaction. However, other myrosinases responsible for turnover of glucosinolates in intact plants have been identified in recent years (

; Wittstock et al., 2016a; b). Some unexpected, non-conventional degradation products have been reported, suggesting a varied and complex metabolism of glucosinolates in intact plants (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). To our knowledge, nothing is known of metabolism or detoxification of OATs in intact plants.

From non-enzymatic breakdown of glucobarbarin and progoitrin catalyzed by high concentrations of ferrous salts, thioamides were reported in high yields, on the base of limited analytical evidence (
; b). A later report provided circumstantial evidence (UV-spectrum of a minor chromatographic peak) for the formation of low levels of the thioamide from epiglucobarbarin at similar high ferrous ion conditions, and discussed the possibility of ferrous ion catalyzed turnover of b -hydroxyalkyl glucosinolates in biological material (
).

We were intrigued by the historical report of 3-hydroxy-3- phenylpropanethioamide (hypothetic “ 5 ”) from glucobarbarin at high ferrous salt concentrations (
) and a tentative later confirmation (
). In an attempt to obtain a reference, the reported procedure (
) was repeated with slight modifications (Section 3.5). Extensive glucobarbarin degradation (92%) after incubation at 15 mM with 150 mM ferrous ammonium sulfate was confirmed by HPLC-analysis ( Fig. 5A ). However, product analysis by HPLC-DAD did not reveal any peak matching the suggested thioamide with ƛ max at 267 nm (
). After extraction with ethyl acetate, the two major products absorbing at 210 nm ( Fig. 5B ) were isolated by HPLC and identified as 3-hydroxy-3-phenylpropanamide ( 8 , tentative) and the nitrile 4 by ion trap HPLC-MS/MS and HPLC-QqToF-MS. Formed along with a nitrile, the amide 8 was considered a reasonable structure, as it can be likened to hydrated nitrile. In the ion trap with eluents doped with NaCl, the sodium adduct was dominant ( Fig. 5C ). The suggested identity was supported by QqToF-MS (found: 166.0866 [MþH] þ , calculated for 8 , [C 9 H 12 O 2 N] þ : 166.0863). Fragmentation of the sodium adduct in ion trap MS supported the identity, as the major loss of 59 amu matched loss of acetamide, leaving an ion with the composition as a sodium adduct of benzaldehyde ( m / z 129). The hydrogen adduct detected in QqToF-MS fragmented differently, with major loss of 60 amu (acetic acid) leaving a fragment matching the composition of phenylmethaniminium ion (found: 106.0653 [M-acetic acidþH] þ , calculated for C 7 H 8 N þ : 106.0651). We find acid-catalyzed rearrangement with loss of acetic acid in agreement with the proposed structure, 8 . Searching the data files after ion trap HPLC-MS of the entire ethyl acetate extract and six isolated peaks did not reveal any sign of the presence of the suggested thioamide “ 5 ”. Specifically, we searched for expected m / z values of hypothetic “ 5 ”: 182 [MþH] þ or 204 [MþNa] þ or 164 [M-H 2 OþH] þ . This expected MS was based on experience with related metabolites 4 , 6 , 7 and 8 ( Figs. 4 and 5 ).

The ion trap mass spectrum of barbarin is characteristic, with major losses of CSO and H 2 S ( Fig. 6C ). The metabolite proving to be resedine showed the same fragments as barbarin, whereas the molecular ions [MþH] þ and [MþNa] þ had m / z values 16 amu lower than those of barbarin ( Fig. 6D ). It seemed obvious that this metabolite was related to barbarin, but with the sulfur replaced by oxygen resulting in losses of CO 2 and H 2 O rather than CSO and H 2 S. Indeed, the UV band from C=S at 242 nm in barbarin was missing (Supplementary Fig. 1 ). For NMR analysis, resedine was isolated by HPLC from foliage autolyzed for 24 h (Supplementary Fig. 2 ). The proton NMR spectrum, with a complex cluster of resonances from the phenyl group in the 7.37‾7.44 ppm interval, and three coupled signals of H5 (5.64 ppm, apparent t), H4a (3.98 ppm, apparent dt) and H4b (3.54, ddd) was in excellent agreement with literature spectra (
;
). First order analysis was not possible, but PERCH analysis confirmed the interpretation and provided accurate chemical shifts and coupling constant values (Supplementary Fig. 3 ). The QqToF-MS confirmed also the interpretations above of MS2 fragmentation, with major losses of H 2 O and CO 2 from the proton adduct. The ion trap HPLC-MS of resedine also agreed with a synthetic specimen prepared from 2 at oxidizing conditions, using H 2 O
2 in
a procedure simplified and scaled down from the literature (Section 3.12).

In order to test whether the catalyst responsible for resedine formation was heat sensitive, an additional experiment was carried out (Section 3.10). First, leaves were homogenized and incubated for 0.3 h, allowing turnover of most of the glucobarbarin to barbarin. Then, the homogenate was divided in aliquots, which were suspended in pH 7 buffer. In order to test for a heat sensitive catalyst without varying total incubation time, all suspended aliquots were incubated for an additional 25 h at room temperature, except for a brief (1 min) boiling at either 0.3 h (i.e. immediately after suspension), 6.3 h or 24.3 h (
Fig. 7B
). Hence, initial glucobarbarin levels were the same in all aliquots, and only the reaction time until boiling varied, not total incubation time or total heat exposure. While total amounts of barbarin and resedine increased slightly between 0.3 h and 6.3 h, the absolute (and also relative) levels of resedine increased in both the 6.3 h and 24.3 h aliquots relative to the 0.3 h aliquot (
Fig. 7B
). In contrast to the experiments comprising autolysis without added buffer, a quasi-linear formation of resedine was not observed. The slower formation after buffer-addition suggested the reaction rate to be very sensitive to dilution of enzyme and/or substrate. As the time until boiling was the only factor varied in the experiment, we concluded that resedine was formed by a heat sensitive catalyst, most likely an enzyme. From a structural argument, barbarin was a likely precursor. In the following, we use the provisional name oxazolidinethionase (OATase) for the hypothesized enzyme. “Thionase” would be a simpler trivial name for an enzyme converting a thiocarbonyl to a carbonyl, but this name was abandoned because it has already been used historically for another enzyme, cystathionine beta synthase, E.C. 4.2.1.22, that catalyzes an apparently unrelated reaction.

It is well established that OATs are unstable at very high temperature, as found in GC instruments (

; 

). Rearrangement to TAOs was reported at GC conditions. Hence, in the experimental design, it was critical that all samples received the same heat treatment, but at different time after homogenization. Clearly, the factor determining the amount of resedine formed was not related to heat energy received, but to the reaction time allowed before heating was carried out. TAOs are detectable at our conditions (Agerbirk and Olsen, 2015), but were not observed, confirming that barbarin was stable at the moderate temperatures used here (100 
ǫC
and below).

Several approaches would be possible for further tests for a metabolic connection of glucobarbarin (
1
) via barbarin (
2
) to resedine (
3
). Mutants devoid of 
1
(

) were not readily available, the enzyme was apparently sensitive to dilution or extraction (
Fig. 7B
), and isotopically labelled precursors were not at hand. Instead, we tested for a more general OAT converting enzyme (OATase): two additional OATs and an OAT precursor glucosinolate were spiked to 

B. vulgaris

homogenates, which were analyzed for the corresponding OAOs after incubation. One of them was (
S
)-5-ethyl-5-methylOAT (
9
), and conversion of this substrate to the corresponding OAO (
10
) was unequivocally demonstrated, as confirmed by the same 
tR
and ion trap MS/MS as that of an authentic standard (
Fig. 8
). This experiment, including relevant controls and testing two different OATs, is detailed below.

We concluded that a heat sensitive factor in 

B. vulgaris

homogenates converts several OATs (
2
, 
9
and 
11
) into corresponding OAOs (
3
, 
10
and 
12
). As autolysis was going on in the homogenate before addition of the spike, and OATase activity was expected to slow down due to the experimental dilution, there was no reason to believe that formation of resedine would be significantly inhibited by one or more added OATs. Test for conversion of (
R
)-goitrin (
11
) was also relevant from an applied perspective, as 
11
is formed from epiprogoitrin in the potential industrial crop 

Crambe abyssinica
Hochst. ex R. E. Fries

(
Brassicaceae
) (

). The (
S
)- goitrin enantiomer was not tested in this work. An OATase enzyme capable of removing the thione functionality of (
S
)-goitrin would seem to have potential in improving the nutritional value of rapeseed (

Brassica napus

) protein that suffer from (
S
)-goitrin and progoitrin contamination (

; 

; 

). Clearly, the natural enantiomer of goitrin in 

Brassica napus

should be used for testing relevant plants for a suitable OATase.

The natural diversity of glucosinolates result in a diverse palette of biological effects, and the diversity is even higher because each glucosinolate can lead to several products (

). Further structural diversity is realized whenever a new 
type
of glucosinolate product is discovered (Agerbirk and Olsen, 2015; 

; 

; 

). Indeed, turnover of OATs to OAOs could be a general reaction happening for several or all of the around 14 known 
b
-hydroxylated glucosinolate side chains (

; 

; 

). OAOs were not detected in a recent, very thorough survey of glucosinolate products in cabbages (

). However, autolysis was only allowed for 0.5 h, and 
b
-hydroxylated glucosinolates were not prominent.

Regulation of the OATase is likely but was not tested. The reaction could be simply a detoxification involved in glucosinolate turnover, possibly allowing sulfur recycling (

). Considering the range of bioactivities of other known OAOs, the reaction could also be involved in defense (

), signaling (

) or biosynthesis. Biosynthesis of non-indole phytoalexins starting from phenethyl glucosinolates in 

B. vulgaris

and 

N. of 
fi
cinale

has already been suggested (

; 

). As the enzyme activity was detected in two plant families, it could be a widespread enzyme involved in turnover of OATs in the 
Brassicales
. Detoxification of contaminating OATs in cruciferous protein would be a potential industrial application of such an enzyme.

Elemental composition and UV spectral data so far constitute the only documentation to support formation of the hypothetic thioamide product “ 
5
” from glucobarbarin (Austin et al., 1068a). However, the general formation of thioamides is better documented (

). 

reported high yields of thioamide from 
b
-hydroxylated glucosinolates but lack of thioamide from a non-hydroxylated glucosinolate, and suggested a mechanism of formation involving the hydroxy group. These authors reported 40% molar yield of the thioamide from epiprogoitrin. However, later authors (

) reported around tenfold lower yield (and the identification of the thioamide was not conclusive). Furthermore, analytical evidence (GC-MS and comparison with an authentic reference) was recently reported for formation of the thioamide from a glucosinolate lacking a hydroxy group (3-methoxybenzylglucosinolate) (

). Hence, formation of thioamides as such from glucosinolates is decently documented, but any influence of the 
b
-hydroxy group is not. Furthermore, the apparently consistent high yields in the pioneering papers (

; b) contrast with the findings of later authors. It seems as if yet unidentified factors influence the possible formation of thioamides from non-enzymatic, ferrous ion catalyzed breakdown of glucosinolates. As the disulfide of thioglucose has been reported to accompany general ferrous ion catalyzed nitrile formation (

), and as we detected amide formation under such conditions as well, a complex reaction involving various other sulfur compounds could be hypothesized. From the perspective of glucobarbarin biology, the results reported here show that formation of a suggested thioamide from glucobarbarin is not easily reproduced and was apparently not of importance at a range of biologically relevant conditions. The latter result had been predicted in a review article (

).

As resedine is not accumulated in intact plants, further metabolism is anticipated 
in vivo
. The committed step would be turnover of the precursor glucosinolate in intact plants, and candidate genes for such turnover were identified in 

B. vulgaris

. Tissue-specific biosynthesis and storage of glucosinolates is well described (

). Localization of a putative OATase could pinpoint sites of turnover. As an alternative to classical isolation and sequencing, we suggest that co-expression analysis (e.g. 

; 

; 

), using the identified genes as leads, could identify the OATase and other enzymes involved in glucosinolate turnover in intact plants.

The genus 

Barbarea

seems to have lost aliphatic glucosinolates and gained diversification of phenethyl and indole glucosinolates and derived compounds (

). The increasingly wellcharacterized wild plant 

B. vulgaris
(
Byrne et al., 2017
)

is polymorphic for a range of defense related metabolites as well as pest- and disease resistances (

). This biochemically innovative plant species would seem to be a valuable genetic resource for a number of traits, including some pathways of glucosinolate turnover and phytoalexin biosynthesis as discussed here.

